'''Heraclides of Tarsus''' ({{lang-grc-gre|Ἡρακλείδης}}, [[Floruit|fl.]] 2nd century BC) was a [[Stoicism|Stoic]] philosopher native to [[Tarsus, Mersin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.attalus.org/names/h/heracleides.html|title=Heracleides - in ancient sources @ attalus.org|work=attalus.org}}</ref> He was a friend of [[Antipater of Tarsus]], the sixth [[scholarch]] of the [[Stoa]].<ref>[[Diogenes Laertius]]. ''Lives and Opinions of Eminent Philosophers''. VII, 121.</ref> As a pupil of Antipater, he studied with Archedemus of Tarsus and [[Aristocreon]], the nephew of [[Chrysippus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=25_SOWldSUUC&pg=PA70&lpg=PA70&dq=heraclides+of+tarsus&source=bl&ots=N49bNM89HR&sig=atrF4JVg7qA7FnsgFdw_oIceL2Q&hl=en&sa=X&ei=sOwiVNi9M8P2yQThroLoCg&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=heraclides%20of%20tarsus&f=false|title=The Origins of the Mithraic Mysteries|work=google.ca}}</ref>

Along with [[Athenodoros Cananites]], Heraclides argued that moral offenses are not equal and have degrees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=40vUmyhRiB4C&pg=PA148&lpg=PA148&dq=heraclides+of+tarsus&source=bl&ots=0KrLhggWpX&sig=AIf6Q4LNxu8FchT3FYJCby1-tgI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=sOwiVNi9M8P2yQThroLoCg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=heraclides%20of%20tarsus&f=false|title=A Summary of Stoic Philosophy|work=google.ca}}</ref>

Remnants of a table of contents from one of the manuscripts (manuscript P) of [[Diogenes Laërtius']] [[Lives and Opinions of Eminent Philosophers]] showed a chapter on the life of Heraclides of Tarsus.{{cn|date=September 2014}}

